<DOC><DOCNO> AP880730-0106 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-30-88 2356EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BoatPeople     07-30 0242</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Boat People,0249</SECOND><HEAD>Hong Kong Opens New Detention Center for Boat People</HEAD><DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government opened another detention centerfor Vietnamese boat people Saturday under a new policy designed tostem the flow of refugees to this British colony.   Despite the new policy's aim, more than 6,700 boat people havesailed into Hong Kong since it went into effect June 15.   About 1,200 refugees were moved Saturday from ferries moored inthe colony's harbor to Erskine Camp, the third temporary detentioncenter for the boat people.   The new policy provides that the Vietnamese be kept in thosecenters until Vietnam agrees to take them back.   Boat people who arrived before the new policy took effect arestill eligible for resettlement. They are kept in refugee centersseparate from the detention centers for recent arrivals.   All boat people arriving after June 15 are considered illegalimmigrants subject to repatriation unless they can prove they fledpersecution in communist Vietnam. The Hong Kong governmentpreviously considered all boat people refugees eligible forresettlement.   More than 16,000 Vietnamese refugees are in Hong Kong.   Also Saturday, Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister Ghafar Baba saidhe will go to Hanoi next month to discuss the refugee issue withVietnamese leaders. Ghafar did not say when his delegation wouldleave for Vietnam, according to Malaysia's Bernama news agency.   It quoted him as saying about 13,000 Vietnamese refugees are inMalaysia awaiting resettlement in other countries.</TEXT></DOC>